{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18771"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10401"},{"type":"tags","id":"10402"},{"type":"tags","id":"10403"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman undergoes overnight polysomnography monitoring in a sleep laboratory. During one phase of sleep, the electroencephalogram shows high-amplitude, low-frequency delta waves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this stage of sleep?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stage 3 non-rapid eye movement sleep","Stage 1 non-rapid eye movement sleep","Stage 2 non-rapid eye movement sleep","Transitional wakefulness","Rapid eye movement sleep"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage 3 non-rapid eye movement sleep\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by high-amplitude delta waves with frequencies less than 4 Hz, occurring in more than 20% of each epoch. This is also known as slow wave sleep and represents the deepest stage of non-rapid eye movement sleep.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage 1 non-rapid eye movement sleep\u003C/strong\u003E features low-amplitude, mixed-frequency activity with prominent theta waves (4-7 Hz)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage 2 non-rapid eye movement sleep\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by sleep spindles and K-complexes with a background of relatively low-amplitude, mixed-frequency activity\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid eye movement sleep\u003C/strong\u003E shows low-amplitude, mixed-frequency waves similar to wakefulness, with characteristic rapid eye movements\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransitional wakefulness\u003C/strong\u003E shows alpha waves (8-13 Hz) when eyes are closed, and faster beta activity when eyes are open\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EDuring stage 3 non-rapid eye movement sleep, muscle tone is decreased but present, eye movements are minimal or absent, and metabolic rate is reduced. This stage is important for physical restoration and growth hormone secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-rapid eye movement sleep consists of three distinct stages characterised by progressively slower brain wave patterns.","Stage 3 non-rapid eye movement sleep (slow wave sleep) features high-amplitude delta waves with frequencies less than 4 Hz.","During non-rapid eye movement sleep, there is decreased muscle tone, minimal eye movements, and reduced metabolic rate."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T13:45:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T13:46:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11503"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type